name: Elizabeth Warren
content:
Here’s why Pharma’s really whining about the COVID vaccine patents: the government might finally have the spine to lower drug prices here at home. And it should.

President Biden can lower drug prices by producing drugs like insulin, naloxone, and EpiPens at low costs. And he doesn’t need Congress to do it – he can use existing compulsory licensing and march-in authorities to bypass patents for public health needs. Drug companies say using these authorities is "radical" and against the free market – but there's nothing radical about using laws, that already exist, to help reduce drug prices for families. We don't work for the drug companies. We work for the people.

U.S. to Back Waiver of Vaccine IP Protections at WTO, Biden Administration Says

name: Rob Portman
content:
Yesterday I led a bipartisan letter with my Senate colleagues calling on the Biden admin to do more to help India combat the COVID crisis. The letter outlined recommendations to:

Work with the Indian government on response, and lead the international efforts to stop the spread of variants and to deliver the assistance needed to the Indian people.

Continue its robust contribution to the COVID-19 Vaccines Global Access Facility’s plan for the global acquisition and distribution of vaccines to low and medium-income countries.

Provide a detailed public strategy on how the Department of State plans to distribute excess vaccines, which would clarify the ambiguity surrounding future US policy and provide needed certainty to India.

Utilize the Global Engagement Center to combat the numerous disinformation messages from Russia, China and others on the coronavirus pandemic, including the US global health response.

name: Benjamin L. Cardin
content:
The American Rescue Plan is investing in our hard-hit small businesses to ensure they can safely reopen and stay open. The plan:

o Allocated $15 billion in flexible grants to help the smallest, most severely impacted businesses persevere through the pandemic.

o Bolstered the Paycheck Protection Program with an additional $7.25 billion in funding to support small businesses and non-profits that were previously excluded, such as businesses owned by women, veterans, and minorities.

o Launched the Restaurant Revitalization Fund to provide $28 billion in relief to restaurants and other hard-hit food establishments — bars, bakeries, food stands, food trucks, caterers – to help businesses get grants to cover payroll, rent, utilities, and supplies.

More than 186,200 eligible businesses have applied for support through the new Restaurant Revitalization Fund in two days, illustrating the ongoing need for creative measures like those in the American Rescue Plan.

I’m proud to have worked, and to continue working, on behalf of Maryland’s small businesses to help find ways the federal government can help them forge a path through the pandemic.

https://www.cnbc.com/2021/05/05/restaurant-revitalization-fund-opens-28-billion-in-grants-up-for-grabs.html

Hard-hit restaurants rush for a lifeline as $28 billion in grants go up for grabs

name: Brian Schatz
content:
Are you a high school student interested in public service? Do you know someone who is? My office is now accepting applications for our High School Internship Program.

This is a great opportunity for students across the state to learn firsthand about the U.S. Senate, take on unique and creative projects, and become leaders and advocates in their schools and communities. Here's what Tiffany-Ryan Kusano, one of our outgoing interns from Roosevelt High School, had to say about her experience:

"I would highly recommend this program to the next eligible class of high school seniors because not only did I gain knowledge, but I contributed to the office in some way. This internship is undeniably a two-way street; you work for both personal experience and community contribution. It is fulfilling to know that you are making a difference at such a young age."

Our program is virtual and designed to limit conflict with classes and extracurricular activities. So no matter where you live in Hawaii, I encourage you to apply.

The deadline to submit your application is September 5, 2021 at 6 p.m. HST, and you can find more information here: https://www.schatz.senate.gov/Services/Internships

April 20 at 10:29 AM ·

LEARN Our Life Skills Enrichment Program offers adults with intellectual and developmental disabilities a wide array of weekday activities that help them create meaningful days, productive years and, ultimately, more fulfilling lives. name: Lisa Murkowski
content: Connecting with Alaskans and hearing directly from them on our state’s greatest needs and priorities is so important as I work to best represent them in the U.S. Senate. I appreciated the discussion I had in Kenai with members of the Kenai Peninsula Economic Development District about their work and partnership with the local businesses, local government, state, and nonprofits, to utilize the federal COVID relief money for maximum benefit. To date, Kenai hasn’t reported a single business closure as a result of the pandemic, and much of that can be attributed to the success of that collaboration. We also spoke about concern over workforce shortages and ways to reverse the Biden administration’s actions where higher unemployment benefits are disincentivizing people to get back to work. As the economy begins to recover and businesses reopen more fully, we discussed innovative ideas to support Alaskans returning to work. This group represents a broad spectrum of the entire peninsula and were able to share with me a number of their priorities for the region, including infrastructure projects, and how I can come alongside them at the federal level.

name: Deb Fischer
content:
Today the U.S. Department of the Interior outlined the Biden administration’s 30x30 proposal for the federal government to conserve 30% of the land by 2030. Despite the lofty principles in this report, we are still nowhere closer to understanding how the administration will accomplish this.

While the administration has made efforts recently to take into account feedback from land owners, farmers, and ranchers, this should have been done prior to announcing the proposal in January.

Nebraskans are worried about this proposal and need information as to how these principles will be implemented.

I will continue to work to ensure Nebraskans have a seat at the table throughout this process, and that their personal property rights are protected.

name: Christopher A. Coons
content:
Today, we are kicking off our National #ServiceShoutout – a chance to shine a light on the programs like AmeriCorps across our country that are helping us build back stronger. Want to know about some of the great work in our state?

🏡 The Ministry of Caring program helped meet the needs of our senior population throughout the pandemic. The program provided resources for hundreds of Delaware seniors last year!

🥘 This past December, the Delaware Foster Grandparents Program partnered with Perdue Farms to launch their annual Chicken Run, delivering the makings of a holiday meal to those vulnerable to food scarcity. The act of kindness helped brighten the holiday season.

📚 Delaware Summer Literacy Corps spent the summer providing daily reading intervention to 1st-5th graders so that no student would be left behind.

👉 Who’s making a difference in your community? Give them a service shoutout!

name: John Boozman
content: I enjoyed getting to spend some time in Piggott today to meet with local leaders for an update on issues of interest and then view the historic “Air Mail” WPA mural at the city’s Post Office which is featured, along with four other Great Depression-era murals, on Forever Stamps. While I was in town, I also got to pay a visit to Hemingway-Pfeiffer Museum & Educational Center to meet with city and county officials and discuss the museum’s proposed restoration project. Then we made the trip over to Corning for lunch at Clay County Electric Cooperative with more area leaders where we discussed the need for increased broadband access, something I’m constantly working on as a co-chair of the Senate Broadband Caucus.

Pleased to learn that Kansas Board of Regents has appointed Dr. Richard Muma as the 15th president of Wichita State University. name: Gus M. Bilirakis
content: During this week’s bipartisan forum on consumer privacy, I stressed my desire to empower consumers while keeping the American virtues of innovation and entrepreneurship alive so new competitors can come in and challenge the big guys. I believe we thrive on backing the underdogs, whether it’s a consumer who wants to ask tough questions about how their data is used, or a startup who wants to challenge an industry titan who already has collected immense data. I also believe there are a few key principles that should be included in any bipartisan agreement: a national privacy framework that will increase transparency and improve accountability, enhance security protections for consumers, and protect innovation and our small businesses. Having a federal privacy standard that protects all Americans is critical.
